SEPAL tutorial: area estimation through stratified sampling

remi.dannunzio@fao.org

May 30, 2017

Getting into SEPAL

SEPAL stands for : System for Earth observations, data access, Processing & Analysis for Land monitoring.

It is a secured cloud-based computing environment for geographical data processing.

It enables users to quickly process large amount of data without high network bandwidth requirements or need to invest in high-performance computing infrastructure.

The platform is still beta and we try to limit the number of users at that stage, so if you want access, you have to request it in this Google Survey



You will then receive an email with a link to activate your access. Remember to check in your SPAMS, it might be there.
This will prompt you to the welcome page of SEPAL. For any further access, simply type https://sepal.io in your browser.



Setup your passord: it needs at least one upper case, one lower case, a letter and a number. The minimum size is 6 digits.

As you will see on the login page or the entry page, there are four main fields in SEPAL:
    SEARCH (for imagery and creating mosaics)
    BROWSE (through your personnal folders and visualize your data)
    TERMINAL (to access all the command lines possibilities of the LINUX server)
    PROCESS (access pre-loaded tools and chains of processing)

For this tutorial, we will use the PROCESS only



Accessing the Stratified Sampling Design tool

Click on process, then click on Stratified Area Estimator - DESIGN



You will get into the introduction page of the tool. You have several boxes with some background information and how to use the tool.

It is available in French, Spanish and English at the moment.

Choose your language in the dropdown menu

Some of the boxes have TABS, like the bottom box where you can access the reference and background documents, including the “good practices for accuracy assessment of land cover change maps” by Olofsson et al. (2014)



The tool functions as a stepwise process that need to be performed in order.

The TABS on the left must be used in descending order:

    Select a map input, that will be the basis of your stratification
    Compute strata areas and name the strata
    Provide parameters to determine the overall sampling size
    Generate sampling points and produce an interpretation interface



1. Select a map input

In step 1, you have to select the map input.


We will see later how to UPLOAD YOUR OWN MAP, but at that stage we will use a test data set with a change map of Congo (CNIAF, 2015).

Click on the “DOWNLOAD TEST DATASET” button


Now you can select the file you downloaded as a MAP INPUT
